          "id": 681,
          "name": "Disabled Person's Travel Pass",
          "description": "<p>The Disabled Person's Pass entitles disabled people to free off peak travel on buses across England (plus additional concessions in South Yorkshire). This is open to people aged 5 to 65 years old. You may be able to qualify for a permit if you:-&#160;</p><ul><li>are registered blind, partially sighted or deaf</li><li>are unable to speak</li><li>have a learning disability registered with Social Services</li><li>have substantial and long-term disabilities or injuries which severely impacts your ability to walk</li><li>are a current blue badge holder</li><li>have lost the use of both arms</li><li>are unable to drive because of a health problem, such as autism or epilepsy</li><li>have, or currently suffer from, a psychiatric disorder, or have an enhanced level care programme approach</li></ul><p>An application form can be found&#160;<a href=\"https://www.sheffield.gov.uk/content/sheffield/home/disability-mental-health/apply-for-disabled-persons-travel-pass.html\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>&#160;<span>and may need to be certified by a medical professional.</span></p><p></p><p>Refused asylum seekers and those with Leave to Remain but No Recourse to Public Funds are still eligible to apply for a Disabled <span>Person's Pass</span><br><br>.</p><p></p><p><br></p>",
