          "id": 881,
          "name": "Care Act Support",
          "description": "<p>If an asylum seeker (age 18+) has significant care and support needs that are related to a physical or mental health issue, illness or disability, they might be able to get housing, financial and other support from the Local Authority social services.&#8203;&#160;</p><p></p><p>Below are details about:</p><ul><li>&#8203;the assessment process</li><li>making a Care Act application</li><li>help to challenge Care Act refusals</li></ul><p></p><p><b>ASSESSMENT PROCESS</b></p><p>The local authority will undertake a two stage assessment:</p><p></p><ul><li><span class=\"rangySelectionBoundary\">&#65279;</span><b>Pre-Assessment Screening</b>: the threshold to carry out an assessment is very low. The council has a duty to assess as long as there is the appearance of need. They will assess:<br>- Does the person ordinarily live in the area.&#160; In cases where people are of no fixed abode, the intention to stay in the locality is sufficient. <br>- Are they in immediate need of being housed?</li><li><b>Assessing eligibility</b>: The threshold for being eligible for support is very high. The person's needs must relate to physical or mental impairment or illness, and must not be a result of them being destitute.&#160; The person must be unable to achieve at least two of the following outcomes&#160; and this must have an impact on their wellbeing.&#160;&#160;These outcomes are:<br>- Managing nutrition<br>- Managing toilet needs<br>- Maintaining personal hygiene<br>- Making use of community facilities and services.</li></ul><p>Note that some refused asylum seekers can only get care and support from social services if this is necessary to prevent a breach of their human rights, so social services&#160;will need to carry out a human rights assessment to establish whether support can be provided.&#160; This has three Stages</p><p><b>1. Can they freely return to their country of origin?</b></p><p>Is there an obstacle to returning, such as missing travel documents, illness that means they can&#8217;t fly, outstanding appeal to the HO?&#160;&#160;If there is a temporary barrier, support could be given temporarily until the barrier is removed and reviewed regularly.&#160;If there is an insurmountable barrier to return, refusing support will probably be a breach of HR</p><p><b>2. What would be the impact of return to their Country of origin on their human rights and would they be breached?</b></p><p>In the case of refused asylum seekers, the opinion of the Home Office is usually available (refusal letter detailing why they believe that the person is not in need of protection).</p><p>However, asylum seekers would need to be given the opportunity to seek legal advice to prove that return&#160; would breach their Human Rights.&#160; It is not sufficient to say that no comparable medical facilities exist in the Country of Origin .</p><p><b>3. Impact on family and private life</b></p><div>What social and family ties the person has in the UK and whether these could be maintained.   Right to family life is a relative right and can be breached if proportionate to legitimate public end. <br></div><p><b>MAKING A CARE ACT APPLICATION</b><br></p><p><b>Red Cross&#160;</b>may be able to support asylum seekers in making a Care Act application - see referral form in Printable Resources.</p><p>GPs may refer people for Care Act assessments</p><p><span class=\"rangySelectionBoundary\">&#65279;</span>Requests for a Care Act Assessment on mental health grounds should be made to the <b>Single Point of Access for&#160;<span>adult community mental health services</span></b><br><br>&#8203;<b>CHALLENGING CARE ACT REFUSALS</b></p><p>Legal aid is available to challenge Care Act decisions from solicitors with public law contracts (e.g. Irwin Mitchell). You can search for legal aid solicitors <a href=\"https://find-legal-advice.justice.gov.uk/\" target=\"\">here,</a>&#160;filter the search by 'public law'.</p><p><b>CAS</b><b>&#160;</b>and <b>Shelter</b> can help people who may wish to question or challenge their Care Act assessments. CAS includes specialist team for deaf people and people with mental health problems.&#160;<br></p><p><b>Further information is available from:</b></p><p>Social Care Institute for Excellence has produced&#160;<a href=\"https://www.scie.org.uk/publications/guides/guide37-good-practice-in-social-care-with-refugees-and-asylum-seekers/background/legislation.asp\" target=\"_blank\">Good practice in social care for refugees and asylum seekers</a></p>",
